The finding was correct and I reproduced it before touching the code. update()'s hole-sunk branch fired purely on geometry — `if(dh<HOLE_R && speed<120)` — with no record that the hole had already been sunk. On a sink it does `game.hole++` and schedules `buildHole()` 600ms later, but leaves `game.state==='playing'`, so update() keeps running past its early-return at line 78 while `ball` and `holePos` still describe the *finished* hole. Friction snaps speed to exactly 0 below 4px/s, so a soft lag putt that dies in the cup leaves the ball parked at `dh≈0, speed=0` — re-satisfying that same test on every subsequent frame and re-running the whole completion branch (bonus score, holeStrokes.push, hole++, another setTimeout) for holes never played. Nothing about it needed player input; the game's own idle loop drove the cascade. Fix is a one-shot latch: `game.sunk` gates the branch and is set on entry, cleared only in buildHole(). Sink detection is now edge-triggered rather than level-triggered on a stale position.</summary>
